    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i heard someone call it \"spooky action at a distance\" once. why do people use that term? it's kind of a weird way to describe physics, right?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That famous phrase was coined by Albert Einstein himself, who was deeply skeptical of the idea that particles could influence each other instantaneously across vast distances. He used it to highlight what he saw as a flaw in quantum mechanics, arguing that it violated the principle of locality and implied \"faster-than-light\" communication, which seemed impossible to him. However, while the term sounds like magic, modern physics has confirmed that these \"spooky\" connections are real, though they cannot actually be used to send usable information faster than light, preserving causality. It's just that the mechanism involves a fundamental link between particles that has no classical equivalent.",
      "source": "target",
